    </div>
   </div>
  </div> and 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="i40" class="math">
    <div class="mrow">
     <span stretchy="false" class="mo">⟨</span>
     <div class="msub">
      <span class="mi">γ</span>
      <span class="mi">A</span>
     </div>
     <span stretchy="false" class="mo">⟩</span>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> as well as the average pollinator and plant abundances, generating a data point in each case. For the reduced model to be a reasonable representation of the real network, the point must be close to the corresponding smooth 2D surface. As shown in 
  <a ref-type="fig" rid="fig01" href="#fig01">Fig. 1</a>, the data points from all 59 empirical real world networks (
  <a ref-type="supplementary-material" rid="d35e1072" href="#d35e1072">
   <span class="italic">SI Appendix</span>, Table S1
  </a>) are near the corresponding surfaces from the reduced model, providing preliminary evidence that the reduced model captures the essential behavior of the real networks from a wide geographical range across continents and climatic zones. As we will show, however, the detailed averaging process can play a role in the model’s predictive power of the average abundances and the tipping point.
 </p>
